entry.title: Don't use PDM::SetProfilesForAllSources() during imports.
entry.content:
PDM::SetProfilesForAllSources(profiles) overwrites all existing profiles

in the PDM with the given profiles. The function's only non-test code

usage is the importing logic. This CL removes this usage, so

SetProfilesForAllSources() can be removed in a follow-up (after cleaning

up some test code).



There are several reasons why we want to get rid of

SetProfilesForAllSources() - in general and specifically in the import

code:

- SetProfilesForAllSources() is (almost) the only usage of enforced

modifications - a hack in the PDM described in

go/pdm-autofill-table-interface. Once the function is gone, the

PDM code can be simplified.

- It will simplify the PDM's interface.

- It's very easy to accidentally wipe all existing profiles.

- Most of the time, imports affect zero or one profiles. Using

SetProfilesForAllSources() just complicates the code, because it

needs to make sure that all unaffected profiles are not wiped.



Changes made by this CL specifically:

During imports, multiple profiles can be silently updated, and at most

one profile is newly imported, updated or migrated. Currently, the code

builds the resulting set of profiles in

ProfileImportProcess::GetResultingProfiles(). This CL introduces

ProfileImportProcess:ImportAffectedProfiles(), which instead calls

PDM::UpdateProfile() for all silently updated profiles and

PDM::AddProfile() or PDM::UpdateProfile() for the new/updated/migrated

profiles.



This is practically no-op. Technically, it introduces a delay between

storing the profiles on import and them being available in the PDM,

since enforced modifications are no longer used.

entry.title: Refactor canvas raster timers
entry.content:
Removed raster timers from Canvas2DLayerBridge into a standalone class

which now integrates with CanvasResourceProvider. The implementation

was simplified by using a RAII model and no longer needs to track

lost contexts because CanvasResourceProvider lifetime management

implicitly takes care of this.



Differences in behaviour with respect to the old implementation:

* The metrics now also track OffscreenCanvases since the timer code

is no longer tied to Canvas2DLayerBridge.

* In the old implementation, async gpu timers were only checked upon

rendering a subsequent frame. This meant that the last frame

rendered to a canvas was never captured, which completely excluded

use cases that draw to a canvas only once, which is fairly common.



This CL also adds unit test coverage for the histogram. In the process

of adding the tests several test helper classes were modified to add

support for unit tests that run on top of the raster interface rather

than the legacy GLES2 interface. In order to make it obvious that a

lot of existing test are still using the legacy interface,

InitializeSharedGpuContext was renamed to

InitializeSharedGpuContextGLES2. and crbug.com/1484858 was created to

follow-up on migrating existing tests to the raster interface.

entry.title: Fix update_client::InstallError overlaps with app installer exit codes
entry.content:
Also, provide a complete set of `CrxInstaller::Results` in the state

change callback.



A `CrxInstaller` instance that runs other application installers needs

the ability to report error codes that `update_client` should not

interpret. For instance:

* the application installer error code may be an OS error code that

overlaps with the error codes in `update_client::InstallError`. Error

code `2` could mean `FINGERPRINT_WRITE_FAILED = 2` or the windows error

`ERROR_FILE_NOT_FOUND`.

* the application installer may report a non-zero success code.

`update_client` views any error code other than `0` as an error.

`ERROR_SUCCESS_REBOOT_INITIATED`, `ERROR_SUCCESS_REBOOT_REQUIRED`, and

`ERROR_SUCCESS_RESTART_REQUIRED` are examples of non-zero success

codes.

With this CL, the `CrxInstaller` may choose to store the application

installer result in `original_error`, and use a zero/non-zero `error`

only to indicate a success/error.



The corresponding changes to the `updater` codebase will be in a

follow-up CL.

entry.title: [omnibox][post-ac] Increase preserve default sync threshold from 3 to 4
entry.content:
Currently, the default suggestion is preserved for

a) async passes, and

b) sync passes if the input is at least 3 characters long.



The threshold for sync passes is useful so that short inputs for which

we aren't sure which suggestions are best don't lock in a suggestion we

later realize is bad.



Rich autocompletion also has a threshold of 3 char inputs. Because it

uses the same threshold, rich autocompletion won't get a chance to

become default when the previous default still matches.



Increasing the preserve threshold to 4 allows the default slot to be

assigned to the highest scoring suggestion for 3 char inputs, and the

rich autocompleted suggestion can compete for it for at least 1 input.



This fixes cases like: https://screenshot.googleplex.com/BVUB2cDriZJuQzD

Where a weak, once-visited 30 days ago suggestion like

'translate.google.com' would always win over a strong, 174 visited

suggestion like 'Chrome/Omnibox Bundled Experiment Trains' for the input

'tra'. A single, old visit could break a user's heavily used

muscle-memory suggestion.

entry.title: Rewrite (behind a flag) HTML direction inheritance and invalidation for dir=auto
entry.content:
This rewrites significant aspects of inheritance of HTML direction

(which affects the unshipped :dir() selector and also the shipped

dirname attribute), including its invalidation, to match current spec

proposals regarding how the inheritance operates on Shadow DOM, and to

improve invalidation in response to dynamic changes. Inheritance of

direction now operates on the node tree, except that shadow roots and

slots both inherit from the shadow host. It previously operated on the

flat tree. This change should not affect the computed values of the CSS

direction property, since the HTML direction is only mapped to CSS

direction on elements where the HTML direction is not inherited.



This also restructures the shadow tree-related invalidation code for

dir=auto to match the changes implemented in

https://crrev.com/26b1b30268b7af4f0e44f298c10338a65e656f40 , which made

dir=auto operate on the node tree, and the additional behavior

implemented in

https://crrev.com/6abc9cbde67c0700be364c7aab86cb29188c7d5d that

implemented special rules (looking at slotted children) for
dir=auto>. Certain text-like form controls also have similar special

rules in which they look at their value. This change can affect the

computed values of the CSS direction property when the direction

computed by dir=auto is different.



The invalidation code for these two distinct things was (in the old

code) too tied together to cleanly separate these changes.



The reason these changes are the next step of work is because they

change (when CSSPseudoDirEnabled) the one caller that passed a

stay_within parameter to CalculateAndAdjustAutoDirectionality that is

different from this; this enables further (smaller) refactoring that I

believe will be needed to fix the failure of

external/wpt/shadow-dom/directionality/dir-shadow-41.html in the

still-unlanded WPT PR at

https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/29820 . I believe this

existing using of stay_within does not make sense; it doesn't make sense

to try to partially traverse the descendants of a dir=auto element with

a different termination point. The traversal of a dir=auto element

should always start at its start and should terminate at the first

strong character or the end of the contents that should influence the

dir=auto. (There are cases where the interaction of the stay_within and

the use of NodeTraversal/FlatTreeTraversal meant that the stay_within

parameter was missed entirely and the tree was searched beyond the

contents that should be; this is a step towards the refactoring needed

to fix that.)



This is based on the proposed behavior described in:

https://github.com/whatwg/html/issues/3699#issuecomment-951423468

which is in the process of being specified in:

https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/9166

https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/9452

https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/9554

entry.content:
(7/8) of TaskQueue lifetime refactor, which will make sequence manager

TaskQueue uniquely owned and a pure virtual interface implemented by

TaskQueueImpl.



TaskQueues are automatically shut down when the object is destroyed,

which is tied to the lifetime of the owning handle. Since there aren't

any use cases for holding onto a queue after shutdown (vs. having a

task runner outlive the queue), this CL makes shutdown private and

replaces it with resetting the handle, which simplifies task queue lifetime.

We added a new keyed service `read_write_cards_manager` in a recent cl.

But we found that there are a few issues to use keyed service:

1. There is existing circular DEPS in existing code, therefore we could

not put the keyed service factory in a component build.

service, but we could not add the new keyed service to the

`OsSettingsManager` DEPS, which adds a new circular DEPS.

3. Keyed service has some overhead that it will be created for each

profile.



Therefore, we decided to use the previous pattern, to add the

`read_write_cards_manager` as a singleton.

entry.title: [Android DevX] Add basic lldb support for Android debugging.
entry.content:
Android NDK has switched from gdb to lldb, and native code debugging

commands such as

$OUTDIR/bin/chrome_public_apk gdb

have been broken for quite a while now.



This CL adds basic lldb support to debug native code on Android on an

attached device, via wrapper script command "lldb". So after buliding

"chrome_public_apk" (with debug info) and after launching Chrome on

device via

$OUTDIR/bin/chrome_public_apk run --args='--wait-for-debugger'

one will be able to run

$OUTDIR/bin/chrome_public_apk lldb

to run lldb-server on-device, then lldb.sh on-client, attached to the

org.chromium.chrome process.



Details:

* Add shell script connect_lldb.sh as the lldb counterpart to

adb_gdb. Only basic feature support have been tested. We might

rewrite the script in Python later.

* Update apk_operations.py to add "lldb" command to wrapper scripts, and

call connect_lldb.sh.



In follow-up CLs we'll add IDE support and documentation updates.

entry.title: Android: Better error messages for ABI mismatch (reland)
entry.content:
Fix:

- When an app's supported lib list is empty, it means that it does not

have a native library. Allow all devices in that case.



Instead of relying on catapult or adb to raise errors, most of which are

not easily translated to an ABI mismatch issue, manually filter devices

in apk_operations.py in order to provide informative error messages when

there are no valid devices to install a given apk or bundle. Some

combinations are listed below, as well as whether they work or have an

error message.



Example devices (ABI lists via ro.product.cpu.abilist):

- emulator API 28 for x86 device, supports: ['x86', 'armeabi-v7a', 'armeabi']

- filtered to just ['x86']

- emulator API 33 for x64 device, supports: ['x86_64']

- pixel 4A for arm64 device, supports: ['arm64-v8a', 'armeabi-v7a', 'armeabi']



Example: Installing trichrome_chrome_bundle with target_cpu="arm" to x86 device

Exception: Cannot find any supported devices for this app.



The device (serial=emulator-5554) is not supported because none of the app's ABIs (arm64-v8a,armeabi-v7a) match this device's ABIs (x86), you may need to set target_cpu="x86" in your args.gn.

entry.title: Replace DeviceAuthRequester with DeviceAuthSource
entry.content:
This CL is part of a bigger refactoring process of the

DeviceAuthenticator class.



DeviceAuthRequester doesn't serve any purpose anymore except inside

some if conditions. But it can be reduced to a smaller enum,

DeviceAuthSource, which can now be passed in the constructor of the

device authenticator, and doesn't need to be sent as a parameter in

the Cancel or Authenticate methods.



DeviceAuthRequester now still exists in ReauthenticatorBridge where,

once it is received from the Java side, it is immediately converted

to DeviceAuthSource. In a later CL, DeviceAuthRequester will be

completely erased from Java side and ReauthenticatorBridge too.

entry.title: [task-attribution] Reland: Move to an implicit GCed task container model
entry.content:
The current task_container_ is a circular buffer with limited space.

That limits the potential use cases for TaskAttribution, and adds

needless complexity. This CL significantly simplifies that model, by

moving the container to be implicit, and relying on GC to clean up tasks

once they are no longer needed - that is, once all their descendent

tasks were done and evicted.



This is a reland of [1], that moves the MessagePort destructor work to

a prefinalizer, to avoid invalid memory reads during destruction.



[1] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4614509
